<br>
The biggest hurdle is public image. The damn Hindenburg disaster. Yes, hydrogen is flammable ñ but so is gasoline. Actually, hydrogen may be much safer than gas ñ if the fuel tank is ruptured (hydrogen will most likely be stored as a gas in a high pressure tank), the hydrogen gas will quickly dissipate. After fifteen minutes a puddle of gasoline is still a fire hazard, but the hydrogen will be gone and present a greatly minimized risk.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, the anti-technological will protest hydrogen cars. You see, the release the most potent greenhouse gas ñ water vapor. Hydrogen cars will be blamed for accelerating global warming (you just cannot win against these people), and they will attribute any increase in rain in an area to the release of the water vapor (flash flood in the desert ñ the evil hydrogen cars are to blame).<br>
<br>
Still, wouldnít it be great. I wish Iceland the best on this one. Just imagine a world where the dependences on foreign oil is reduced or eliminated. No need to drill in environmentally sensitive areas. Fewer ugly oil rigs on the coasts and less crap in the air.<br>
<br>
Currently, the enviro-wackies are pushing for electric cars, a solution I am against. Batteries are a toxic nightmare (lead, acid, yech!), and all they do is shift the point of origin for pollution, something the nutjobs apparently do not comprehend. The electricity has to be produced somewhere, and the most common means is by coal or oil power plants (nasty places). <br>
<br>
Hydrogen will also require electricity, to crack the water. I know a gentleman who uses a windmill to provide the electricity he needs to produce hydrogen, which he uses to fuel his workshop (just a small Bunsen burner and heater). I donít know if you could produce the volume a car would need efficiently with such a setup.<br>
<br>
I use to have some good links to hydrogen power sites, but I have apparently misplaced them. I will dig around and post a few up when I find them.<br>
